<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_ScalarProductLinearTrafo"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Scalar product  of a linear map is linear</caption>
   <associate type="Comment">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Comment: What does this proposition tell us?</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>This proposition gives us two strong pieces of information:</para.body>
         </para>
         <ol>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The scalar product of a linear transformation by a number is again linear</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>If the linear map <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> is represented by <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>, then the linear map <math>
                        <latex>(tL)</latex>
                     </math> is represented by the scalar product <math>
                        <latex>(t\cdot \Mtrx{A})</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ol>
         <para>
            <para.body>In short: the scalar product  of a linear map corresponds to the scalar product of the representing matrix.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>If <math>
               <latex>L\from \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[m]</latex>
            </math> is a linear transformations and <math>
               <latex>t\in \RNr</latex>
            </math> is a number, the scalar product of <math>
               <latex>L</latex>
            </math> by <math>
               <latex>t</latex>
            </math>
         </para.body>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>scalar product</term>
            <term>of a linear transformation</term>
            <term>represented by scalar product of matrix</term>
         </index.glossary>
      </para>
      <math.display>
         <latex>(tL)\from \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[m],\quad (tL)(\Vect{x}) = t\cdot L(\Vect{x})</latex>
      </math.display>
      <para>
         <para.body>is again linear. Moreover, if <math>
               <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
            </math> is the <math>
               <latex>(m,n)</latex>
            </math>-matrix representing <math>
               <latex>L</latex>
            </math>, then <math>
               <latex>(t\cdot \Mtrx{A})</latex>
            </math> represents <math>
               <latex>(tL)</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <caption>Linearity of <math>
               <latex>(tL)</latex>
            </math>
         </caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>(tL)</latex>
               </math> satisfies the properties of a linear transformation. To see that it commutes with vector addition, let <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x},\Vect{y}\in \RNr[n]</latex>
               </math>. We find</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>(tL)(\Vect{x}+\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>This is the definition of <math>
                                 <latex>(tL)</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot L(\Vect{x}+\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>As <math>
                                 <latex>L</latex>
                              </math> is linear.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot L(\Vect{x}) + t\cdot L(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>tL(\Vect{x}) + tL(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>(tL)(\Vect{x})\ +\ (tL)(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>So <math>
                  <latex>(tL)</latex>
               </math> commutes with vector addition.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>To see that <math>
                  <latex>(tL)</latex>
               </math> commutes with scalar multiplication, let <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}\in\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>a\in\RNr</latex>
               </math>. We find:</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>(tL)(s\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>This is the definition of <math>
                                 <latex>(tL)</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot (L(a \Vect{x}) )</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>... because <math>
                                 <latex>L</latex>
                              </math> is linear</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot ( aL(\Vect{x}) )</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>(ta)\cdot L(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>s\cdot \left( t\cdot L(\Vect{x}) \right)</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>a\cdot (tL(\Vect{x}))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>This means that <math>
                  <latex>(tL)</latex>
               </math> commutes with scalar multiplication. – The proof that <math>
                  <latex>(tL)</latex>
               </math> is linear is complete.</para.body>
         </para>
         <caption>The matrix which represents <math>
               <latex>(tL)</latex>
            </math>
         </caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>We know now that <math>
                  <latex>(tL)</latex>
               </math> is linear. Therefore there is a unique <math>
                  <latex>(m,n)</latex>
               </math>-matrix  which represents it. On the other hand, if <math>
                  <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
               </math> represents <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math>, we find for arbitrary <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}\in\RNr[n]</latex>
               </math>
            </para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>(tA)\Vect{x} = t\cdot (A \Vect{x}) = t\cdot ( L(\Vect{x}) ) = (tL)(\Vect{x})</latex>
         </math.display>
         <para>
            <para.body>Therefore <math>
                  <latex>\Mtrx{C}:=t\Mtrx{A}</latex>
               </math> is the unique matrix representing <math>
                  <latex>(tL)</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
